summary: My Predictions for GoT:
title: My Predictions for GoT:
body:
-Jon and Dany are NOT a couple.

Because I don’t think either of them would want to be together after finding out THE TRUTH about their shared family roots. Dany is unstable and her incestuous bloodline isn’t helping; and bestowing that on a child is even worse. Jon is too moral for that noise. But, of course, there is going to be a child, because of that stupid prophecy. I’m sure they passed an island, or something about Jon being undead, that will fit the requirements and she’ll find she’s with child. They will try to keep it a secret, but Tyrion knows and is dragged into it all as well (that’s the only reason I can think of for why they would make a stink for us to see that Tyrion knows that they had relations).

-Sansa and Tyrion will renew their marital contract as a political move.

It will be Sansa’s idea, as she is not interested in love sustaining her; she’s in love with Winterfell and it’s people, and that’s enough for her. But to avoid suitors coming at her and being manipulated for political gain ever again, she proposes renewing her marriage to Tyrion, as he has always been kind to Sansa and respects her. If she can produce at least one child, then she has someone to pass Winterfell on to, and it can eventually unite Starks and Lannisters. Tyrion will comply, even though he knows it’s not for love… but of course my shippers heart would hope that eventually his expert gentleness can teach Sansa to enjoy her body, despite the scars. And they get along so well, as master politicians… and could probably learn to love each other for their intelligences. And the union pleases “The Rightful Queen”… though I don’t think Sansa would really care about that.

-Jon (or Sansa) takes the Westeros throne, but only until Dany’s child comes of age.

This fulfills a few loose ends. When the Mad King was slain, everyone expected Stark to step up and take the throne, as they all could unite under the righteous and honest Neddard Stark. But Robert Baratheon did instead. So it’s gotta be a Stark…but the end result is King’s Blood, and a female: Cersei’s prophecy is that she will lose all of her children and that a younger, more beautiful queen will take her place on the throne. So she finds all queen contenders a major threat… but how ironic would it be if the future queen to take her place was actually an infant she doesn’t even know about, rather than all the ladies that are currently posing a threat? So it’s gotta be a Stark, Kings Blood, and a female. I believe it will be Dany’s daughter. 

-Dany dies in child-birth.

I’m over Dany. And it would be poetic irony that the mother of dragons, breaker of chains, slave mother who can conquer and is the most beautiful and blah blah blah… meets her end with something as ordinary as childbirth. I know alot of people don’t like that idea… But I don’t care. I don’t see her going down in a blaze of glory with a gooey death scene (because she’s unbeatable with her dragons)…but she will die. She’s been built up too much to be the winner they are all expecting. She gonna die. And she’s going to bring in the queen of prophecy in the process.

-Gendry is supposed to take the throne, but refuses to in order to live a more simple life with Arya.

But our girl isn’t about to settle down as a Lord’s Lady. She protects her sister as a personal body guard and takes care of unsavory enemies. Gendry will have her any way he can, so he acts as her informant and partner in arms…and of course, something more as they get older. But as man and wife… not so sure about that. She’s only his lady in private.

-Cersei Dies, and it’s Jamie who does the deed.

She’s gots to go, and he knows it. I’m really hoping that her current child comes out hideously deformed from the incest…or a dwarf… and dies right after birth. This drives Cersei even more mad and she makes some shocking decisions that even Jamie can’t overlook…and he is once again placed in the position to take down the monarch he swore to protect. It will probably be revealed that he is the “little brother” that is supposed to kill her… as he was delivered second at their birth. Jamie will not survive this trauma and will want to die with dignity.

-The white walkers are not beatable enemies, and a co-existence with this entity will have to be struck. It is the last of a magical race that was worshipped and will never truly be gone.

That’s all I got. It would just be really disappointing for the WW’s to be beaten abruptly in one season after seasons of build-up. I think there is a lesson to be learned. I’m just hazy on what it is. I’m sure it will be very Ferngully.

summary: I'm reading a book about the American revolution and apparently there was a colonel named John Stark! I'm sure it's a reach in...
body:
I’m reading a book about the American revolution and apparently there was a colonel named John Stark! I’m sure it’s a reach in regards to Jonsa bt I just found it amusing that he led an inexperience army against mercenaries and said “They were bought for seven pounds and ten pence a man. Are you worth more? Prove it!”

Although that might not be what Jon Snow would say seems relevant knowing that both Cersei and Daenerys have “outsiders” (the golden company for cersei and the unsullied for Dany) in their armies. So the North and other house might also need to be rallied up for battle when odds are against them.

Ps. It’s a fun American fact also

summary: Bartender AU
title: Bartender AU
body:
Jon work as a bartender as what most people would call a dive bar, with tables scratched by pen knives, an old melted wax candle tower by the cash register, and nuts bowls along the bar. Most of their clients are regulars, including a struggling writer (Sam), a blind war-veteran (Aemon), and a bunch of blue collars workers. Jon’s boss is an asshole, but he isn’t around much. Overall he likes his work, way better than his previous one at a posh restaurant filled with rich, stuck-up assholes.

But one night, a drunk wandering bachelorette party go in. Jon uses his knowledge of the previous posh job to whipped up some cocktails and they love them. Suddenly they become a must for college’s girls and other bachelorette’s parties.
